    <h1>Project Overview</h1>

    <p>
        <strong>Project 1 â€“ Indexer/Search</strong> is part of the Fall 2024 curriculum for the course 
        <em>Object-Oriented Programming</em> at Texas Tech University. The purpose of this project is to develop a 
        simple but effective indexer/search engine that allows users to search through various types of documents, 
        such as text files, PDFs, and others, using an efficient algorithmic approach.
    </p>

    <p>
        The search engine supports recursive folder indexing, which enables users to retrieve relevant documents based on a 
        given query. The project focuses on implementing well-known algorithms such as <strong>TF-IDF</strong> for document 
        indexing and <strong>Cosine Similarity</strong> for determining the similarity between documents. 
    </p>

    <p>
        This project provides two main interaction interfaces: a <strong>Command Line Interface (CLI)</strong> and a 
        <strong>Graphical User Interface (GUI)</strong>. Both interfaces adhere to good Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) 
        practices and the SOLID principles. The system is also designed with extensibility in mind, allowing for the future 
        addition of new file types without major structural changes to the existing code.
    </p>

    <p>
        As search engines like Google have shown, indexing and searching through large collections of documents is 
        crucial in the modern information age. While our project operates on a much smaller scale, it mimics the core 
        principles behind search engines and highlights the importance of data indexing and efficient retrieval.
    </p>

